questions.questionText: int sum(int n){ if(n==0)return 0; else return n+sum(n-1);    What is the runtime complexity of this statement?
questions.response: There are no recursions or anything of the sort and the algorithim runs at a solid O(n)

questions.questionText: Which is the worst time complexity
questions.response: O(n!) is the worst time complexity that a program can have

questions.questionText: Write an int statement n that holds the value 9 in java(In the way of int n=[numbers]);
questions.response: The right code is int n=9;

questions.questionText: Which is the best time complexity out of all the options
questions.response: O(n) is the second best time complexity that a program can have

questions.questionText: Which is the best time complexity out of all the options
questions.response: O(1) is the best time complexity that a program can have

questions.questionText: O(log n) is better and faster than O(n)
questions.response: O(log n) is one of the fastes runtimes

questions.questionText: O(log n) and O(1) run almost the same in terms of speed
questions.response: O(log n) and O(1) are both excellent runtimes and almost run at the same speed

questions.questionText: Big O notation is one of the best ways to determine how fast a program can run
questions.response: Big O notation is widely amongst all programmers to determine runtime complexities
